<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06256204 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06256204 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  GARDEN; BRIEF  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Begonias, by golly; Dan Englund of Monterey will discuss his specialty, canebegonias, at the meeting of Santa Clara Valley Begonia Society next Thursdayat 7 p.m. The program will be held in Kirk Community Center, 1601 FoxworthyAve., San Jose. Free.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Garden  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  THE WEEKEND GARDENERBEST BET  </HEADLINE><TEXT>   BEST BUY; Budget bloomers; Many nurseries are clearing out summer floweringplants to make way for fall stock. Look for garden mums, priced from $2.50 inone-gallon containers; azaleas, from $5 in one-gallon containers, and treeroses, from $12 in two-gallon containers.; VEGETABLES; Pinch tomatoes; Pinchblooms off tomato plants to direct their energy into fruit that already hasset (started to develop). Tomatoes that set after Labor Day fail to mature intime for harvest before the first frost. Fruit toward the end of the season isalways smaller than the first fruit of the summer.; FREEBIES; Get a catalog;Whether you need information on drought-time water management or pestmanagement, the University of California's updated publications catalog is thebook for you. The 1991 catalog contains hundreds of titles on field crops,soil, chemicals, farm management, forestry, fruits and more. The catalog canbe ordered free from ANR Publications, Dept. NR, University of California,Oakland 94608-1239. It is also available from most county CooperativeExtension offices, and from the Agricultral Information and Publicationsoffice at the University of California, Davis.; YOUR CHECKLISTY; (box) Prolongblooming on tuberous begonias, dahlias and fuchsias by pinching off fadedflowers.; (box) Divide and replant crowded perennials.; (box) Trim beardediris foliage to fans six inches from the rhizomes.; (box) Plant new irises anddivide others if they failed to bloom well this year.; (box) Plant autumnblooming crocus now for a harvest of true saffron in November.; (box) Dryflowers for arrangements.; (box) Shape evergreen hedges for the last time thisyear.; (box) Disbud camellias, leaving only one bloom bud per branch to getthe largest blossoms.; THE LAST WORD; Hand in glove; Disposable latex or vinylgloves like the ones dentists use are useful in the garden too. Tough, yetallowing sensation, they are good for plucking insect pests off tomato andbean plants and protecting hands digging in wet soil. A box of 100 costs lessthan $20 at the grocery or drugstore and should last several years.  </TEXT><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910912  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Thursday  </DAY><MONTH>  September  </MONTH><PG.COL>  3D  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  385  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Thursday, September 12, 199100256204,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>